An InheritedWidget in Flutter is a type of Stateful Widget that provides its descendants with read-only, rebuildable, and tree-wide accessible data. It achieves this by creating an inheritance mechanism for widgets in a subtree. The idea is to have a single source of truth for a piece of data that can be easily accessed by all widgets in the subtree without having to pass the data down through every level of the widget tree as props.

To use an InheritedWidget, you create a new class that extends `InheritedWidget` and overrides the `build(BuildContext context)` method to return the InheritedWidget itself. You then provide a constructor that accepts the `child` argument, which will be the widget that you want to wrap, and the `value` argument, which is the data you want to make available to the subtree.

