In Dart, there isn't a concept of extension methods as in languages like C# or Kotlin. However, you can achieve similar functionality using mixins or static methods in classes. Here are both approaches:

1. Mixins:
Create a new mixin containing the desired method(s) and apply it to the target class:

```dart
mixin StringExtensions {
  String capitalize() => this[0].toUpperCase() + substring(1);
}

class MyClass extends Object with StringExtensions {
  final String name = "John Doe";

  void main() {
    print(name.capitalize); // prints "John Doe"
  }
}
```

2. Static methods:
Define the static method outside the target class, but make sure to include an instance of the target class as the first argument:

```dart
extension StringExtensions on String {
  String capitalize() => this[0].toUpperCase() + substring(1);
}

class MyClass {
  final String name = "John Doe";

